Franz Xaver Wolfgang Mozart (1791–1844)

**Franz Xaver Wolfgang Mozart**

![Franz Xaver Wolfgang Mozart (1825)](/File:Franz_Xaver_Wolfgang_Mozart.jpg)
Franz Xaver Wolfgang Mozart (1825)

| Born | (1791-07-26)July 26, 1791<br />[Vienna](/Vienna) |
| :--- | :------------------------------------------------ |
| Died | July 29, 1844(1844-07-29) (aged 53)<br />[Karlsbad](/Karlovy_Vary) |
| Parents | • [Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart](/Wolfgang_Amadeus_Mozart)<br />• [Constanze Weber](/Constanze_Mozart) |

Franz Xaver Wolfgang Mozart (26 July 1791 – 29 July 1844), a man condemned by birthright, was also known, perhaps inevitably, as Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart Jr. He was the sixth and youngest child born to the monumental composer [Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart](/Wolfgang_Amadeus_Mozart) and his resilient wife [Constanze](/Constanze_Mozart). Of their six offspring, he was the younger of the two who managed to survive past infancy, a rather grim distinction in that era. [^1] This individual, burdened by a name that simultaneously opened doors and cast an inescapable shadow, forged a career as a [composer](/Composer), accomplished [pianist](/Pianist), capable [conductor](/Conducting), and diligent teacher. His active years spanned the twilight of the [classical period](/Classical_period_(music)) and the nascent stirrings of [Romanticism](/Romanticism). His musical style, unsurprisingly, bore the indelible mark of his father’s mature genius, though he occasionally hinted at a burgeoning, more contemporary voice. Despite the constant, crushing comparison, he managed to earn the respect of his peers, including such luminaries as [Franz Schubert](/Franz_Schubert) and [Robert Schumann](/Robert_Schumann), both of whom, astonishingly, held him in high esteem.

### Biography

Franz Xaver Wolfgang Mozart had the rather dramatic timing to be born in [Vienna](/Vienna) a mere four months and ten days before his father’s untimely death. One might call it a cosmic irony; the passing of one genius coinciding with the arrival of another, destined to live in his shadow. Although he was formally baptized Franz Xaver Mozart, his family, with a touch of either affection or unintentional cruelty, consistently referred to him as Wolfgang. [^2] One can only imagine the weight of that name, the constant reminder of an impossible legacy.

Despite this psychological burden, his early musical education was nothing short of exceptional, a testament to his mother’s determination and the connections his father had cultivated. He received rigorous instruction from some of the most respected figures of the time, including the formidable [Antonio Salieri](/Antonio_Salieri) – a name that, for different reasons, also carries a heavy historical weight – and the virtuosic [Johann Nepomuk Hummel](/Johann_Nepomuk_Hummel). For composition, he studied under the tutelage of [Johann Georg Albrechtsberger](/Johann_Georg_Albrechtsberger), a renowned theorist, and the prolific [Sigismund von Neukomm](/Sigismund_von_Neukomm). [^3] He dedicated himself to mastering both the [piano](/Pianist) and the violin. Like his illustrious father before him, he began to compose at a remarkably early age. His public debut in [Vienna](/Vienna) occurred in April 1805, when the thirteen-year-old Wolfgang Mozart Jr. performed in a concert at the prestigious [Theater an der Wien](/Theater_an_der_Wien). [^4]

![Two surviving sons of Wolfgang Amadeus and Constanze Mozart: Franz Xaver Wolfgang (left) and Karl Thomas (right); painting by Hans Hansen, Vienna, 1800](/File:Mozart_Sons_by_Hans_Hansen.jpg)
The two surviving sons of [Wolfgang Amadeus](/Wolfgang_Amadeus_Mozart) and [Constanze Mozart](/Constanze_Mozart): Franz Xaver Wolfgang (left) and [Karl Thomas](/Karl_Thomas_Mozart) (right); painting by [Hans Hansen](/Hans_Hansen_(Danish_painter)), Vienna, 1800 (circa 1800)

Mozart eventually established himself as a professional musician, achieving what could be described as moderate success, particularly in his roles as a teacher and performer. However, his temperament stood in stark contrast to the often flamboyant and confident image of his father. Franz Xaver was notably introverted, plagued by a pervasive sense of self-deprecation. He harbored a deep-seated fear that his own creative output would forever be judged, and inevitably found wanting, when measured against the colossal achievements of his father. This internal struggle led him to constantly undervalue his own considerable talents, a perfectly understandable neurosis given the circumstances. Imagine being named 'Junior' to a legend, a perpetual footnote to greatness.

Financial necessity, that most insistent of muses, compelled him to leave [Vienna](/Vienna) in 1808. He journeyed to Lemberg (which is known today as [Lviv](/Lviv) in [Ukraine](/Ukraine)), where he secured employment giving music lessons to the daughters of the Polish count Wiktor Baworowski. While the remuneration was certainly adequate, Franz found himself profoundly lonely in the isolated town of Pidkamin, situated near [Rohatyn](/Rohatyn). Consequently, in 1809, he accepted a more appealing offer from another Polish aristocrat, the [imperial](/Austrian_Empire) [chamberlain](/Chamberlain_(office)), Count von Janiszewski. This new position involved teaching his daughters music in the town of [Burshtyn](/Burshtyn). Beyond his teaching duties, he also began to give local concerts, performing both his own compositions and, perhaps to appease expectations, pieces by his father. These performances proved instrumental in introducing him to the influential social and cultural circles of [Galicia](/Galicia_(Eastern_Europe)).

After dedicating two years to his work in [Burshtyn](/Burshtyn), he made a significant move to Lemberg ([Lviv](/Lviv)) in 1813. This city would become his primary residence for the next quarter-century, a substantial period during which he immersed himself in teaching – his students included [Julie von Webenau](/Julie_von_Webenau), née Baroni-Cavalcabò, a notable composer in her own right – and continued to give concerts. Between 1826 and 1829, he undertook the ambitious task of conducting the choir of Saint Cecilia, an ensemble comprising a remarkable 400 amateur singers. In 1826, he conducted his father’s iconic [Requiem](/Requiem_(Mozart)) during a concert held at the [Ukrainian Greek Catholic](/Ukrainian_Greek_Catholic_Church) cathedral of [St. George](/St._George%27s_Cathedral,_Lviv). From the foundations of this large choir, he established the musical brotherhood of Saint Cecilia, which subsequently evolved into the first formal school of music in Lemberg, a significant contribution to the region’s cultural landscape. He did not, however, abandon his performing career, and between 1819 and 1821, he embarked on several concert tours throughout Europe. In 1819 alone, he gave concerts in [Warsaw](/Warsaw), [Elbing](/Elbl%C4%85g) (modern-day Elbląg), and Danzig ([Gdańsk](/Gda%C5%84sk)).

During the 1820s, Mozart Jr. found himself among a distinguished group of 50 composers commissioned to contribute a [variation](/Variation_(music)) on a theme by [Anton Diabelli](/Anton_Diabelli). This collective effort formed Part II of the monumental [Vaterländischer Künstlerverein](/Vaterl%C3%A4ndischer_Künstlerverein). Part I of this ambitious project, for context, was famously dedicated entirely to the 33 variations supplied by [Beethoven](/Ludwig_van_Beethoven), which have since achieved an independent and legendary status as his [Diabelli Variations](/Diabelli_Variations), Op. 120. It was around this period that Mozart Jr. made the acquaintance of [Franz Schubert](/Franz_Schubert), and the two musicians developed a close friendship that lasted until Schubert’s untimely death in 1828.

![Lithograph of the composer in his latter years, by Josef Kriehuber](/File:Franz_Xaver_Wolfgang_Mozart_Josef_Kriehuber.jpg)
Lithograph of the composer in his latter years, by [Josef Kriehuber](/Josef_Kriehuber)

In 1838, after his extensive period in [Lemberg](/Lviv), Mozart Jr. moved back to [Vienna](/Vienna), and subsequently to [Salzburg](/Salzburg), the city of his father’s birth. There, he was appointed as the [Kapellmeister](/Kapellmeister) (music director) of the prestigious [Mozarteum](/Mozarteum), a position that must have felt both a homecoming and a constant reminder of his lineage. From 1841, he took on the role of teacher to the promising young pianist [Ernst Pauer](/Ernst_Pauer). Franz Xaver Wolfgang Mozart succumbed to [stomach cancer](/Stomach_cancer) on 29 July 1844, just three days after his 53rd birthday, in the spa town of Karlsbad (now known as [Karlovy Vary](/Karlovy_Vary) in the Czech Republic), where he was subsequently buried.

Like his elder brother, [Karl Thomas Mozart](/Karl_Thomas_Mozart), Franz Xaver Wolfgang remained unmarried and childless throughout his life. His will was meticulously executed by Josephine de Baroni-Cavalcabò (1788–1860), a woman who had been a devoted patron to him for many years and to whom he had dedicated his cello sonata. [^3]

The immense shadow of his father, it seems, extended even beyond the grave. The following poignant [epitaph](/Epitaph) was etched onto his [tombstone](/Tombstone): "May the name of his father be his epitaph, as his veneration for him was the essence of his life." A rather fitting, if utterly crushing, summation of a life lived under a shadow.

### Works by genre

Franz Xaver Wolfgang Mozart’s compositional output was, by most measures, relatively modest, with his opus numbers extending only to 30. Furthermore, after 1820, he appears to have largely curtailed his compositional activities; a particularly striking gap of eleven years (from 1828 to 1839) suggests a period where he seemingly produced nothing. One can only speculate on the reasons – creative exhaustion, the weight of expectation, or simply a shift in focus. Nevertheless, his music is not entirely forgotten, and recordings of his works can be found today, allowing a glimpse into his distinct, if overshadowed, voice. He primarily focused on [chamber music](/Chamber_music) and [piano music](/Piano_music), with his most substantial contributions to the orchestral repertoire being his two [piano concertos](/Piano_concerto).

