#### Concertante

*   [Piano Concerto No. 1 in C major](/Piano_Concerto_No._1_(F.X.W._Mozart)), Op. 14 (composed in 1808, published in 1811)
*   [Piano Concerto No. 2 in E-flat major](/Piano_Concerto_No._2_(F.X.W._Mozart)), Op. 25 (composed in 1818)

These two [piano concertos](/Piano_concerto) exhibit noticeable differences, reflecting a subtle evolution in his style. The first concerto, Op. 14, could, with a certain leniency, almost be mistaken for one of his father’s later works (those from K. 550 onwards), distinguished primarily by a youthful exuberance and the expanded [tessitura](/Tessitura) of the piano part, a development that occurred around 1795, shortly after Mozart senior’s death. The second concerto, Op. 25, however, feels more contemporary to the 1810s, featuring a more overtly virtuosic piano part. This later work offers stronger hints that the younger Mozart was indeed developing a distinct stylistic identity, moving beyond mere imitation.

