### Liszt misattribution

Perhaps one of the more ironic twists in Franz Xaver Mozart’s already overshadowed career involves his *Five Variations on a romance from [Méhul](/%C3%89tienne_M%C3%A9hul)'s [Joseph](/Joseph_(opera))*, Op. 23, first published in 1820. For decades, and until as recently as 1994, this particular work was mistakenly attributed to the young [Franz Liszt](/Franz_Liszt). The error originated from a copyist's manuscript of the piece, which bore the unfortunately misleading notation "par le jeune Liszt" (by the young Liszt). This misattribution was so widely accepted that the work was published in good faith by the *Neue Liszt-Ausgabe* in 1990 and subsequently catalogued as Liszt's S147a.

The esteemed [Liszt](/Franz_Liszt) scholar [Leslie Howard](/Leslie_Howard_(musician)) even recorded the work in similar good faith in 1992 as part of his monumental series of recordings encompassing the complete music for solo piano by [Liszt](/Franz_Liszt), specifically for the disc titled *The Young Liszt*. However, shortly after the disc’s release, Howard himself discovered and noted the error in his accompanying sleeve notes:

> It has since been established that the attribution is false and that the work is from the pen of Mozart’s son Franz Xaver and was published as his opus 23 in 1820. But since the work remains unknown and unrecorded, like the vast majority of F X Mozart's output, and since the writing is not vastly different from some of the other pieces in this collection, it was thought best not to discard it. [^6]

The irony is palpable: a piece by the son of *Mozart*, a name synonymous with musical genius, was so overlooked that it had to gain recognition under the guise of *another* colossal figure, [Liszt](/Franz_Liszt). It speaks volumes about the pervasive shadow of his father and the struggles Franz Xaver faced in carving out his own identity, even posthumously.

### Monuments

In a rather delayed, but perhaps still meaningful, gesture of recognition, a monument dedicated to Franz Xaver Wolfgang Mozart has been erected in [Lviv](/Lviv), [Ukraine](/Ukraine), specifically in Yevhena Malanyuka Square. A monument, after a life spent in shadows. Humanity's timing is impeccable.

